04079nam a22006495i 9780226567150DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017054843  a9780226567150  a(DE-B1597)525047  a(OCoLC)1038796985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN173b.R37 2018 4aPN173 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a808.00922231 aReames, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeming and Being in Plato’s Rhetorical Theory /cRobin Reames. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 line drawing, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION. Literacy, Dramatic Form, Metaphysics -- t1. The “Cosmetics” of Sophistry -- t2. The Oral Poet and the Literate Sophist -- t3. Heraclitean Opposition and Parmenidean Contradiction -- t4. Sophistry without Measure, Dialectic without Rhetoric -- t5. The Rhetoric of Mimêsis -- t6. Imitators of Truth -- tEPILOGUE. The Past and Future of Plato’s Rhetorical Theory -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe widespread understanding of language in the West is that it represents the world. This view, however, has not always been commonplace. In fact, it is a theory of language conceived by Plato, culminating in The Sophist. In that dialogue Plato introduced the idea of statements as being either true or false, where the distinction between falsity and truth rests on a deeper discrepancy between appearance and reality, or seeming and being. Robin Reames’s Seeming & Being in Plato’s Rhetorical Theory marks a shift in Plato scholarship. Reames argues that an appropriate understanding of rhetorical theory in Plato’s dialogues illuminates how he developed the technical vocabulary needed to construct the very distinctions between seeming and being that separate true from false speech. By engaging with three key movements of twentieth- and twenty-first-century Plato scholarship—the rise and subsequent marginalization of “orality and literacy theory,” Heidegger’s controversial critique of Platonist metaphysics, and the influence of literary or dramatic readings of the dialogues—Reames demonstrates how the development of Plato’s rhetorical theory across several of his dialogues (Gorgias, Phaedrus, Protagoras, Theaetetus, Cratylus, Republic, and Sophist) has been both neglected and misunderstood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aRhetoricxPhilosophy. 0aSophists (Greek philosophy) 0aSophists (Greek philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aPlato.  abeing.  alogos.  amimêsis.  aonoma.  arhetoric.  arhetorical theory.  arhêma.  aseeming.  asophists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226567150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226567150/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles